# Play songs with a buzzer

## 1. Overview

In this lesson you will learn how to play songs using the buzzer. We have
created two songs that you can play with the buzzer. If you are more talented, you
can write more complicated songs.

## 2. Components required

* Development board
* Breadboard 830p
* 1 x passive buzzer
* Diode
* Transistor
* 2 x push button
* 1 x 1000 Ω resistor
* 12 x male-to-male jumper wires
* Micro USB – Type A USB cable

## 3. Connections
  Below you can find the schematic:

In the next diagram we have as main elements the buttons, the transistor and the buzzer.

To connect the buttons we will make the connection of the pins on the diagonal to avoid the short circuit. 

The transistor will have the collector pin connected to ground, the base pin connected by a resistor to one of the pins on the board and the emitting pin will be connected to our buzzer by a diode to avoid polarity reversal. 

The other pin of the buzzer is connected to the voltage.
  
  Below, you can find a visual representation of the project:

## 4. Code

### Import libraries
First, we import libraries to later use the functions and variables predefined in them.

#use these libraries to declare used pins and PWM
from machine import Pin, PWM
#for delay
from time import sleep

### Declaration variables
The code starts with the declaration of the pins used by the buttons and the buzzer. 

We first declare as an input pins ('Pin.IN') and pull up pins ('Pin.PULL_UP') the buttons and as output pin ('Pin.OUT') the buzzer.
With the initiation of the pin used by the buzzer, we declare it as PWM.

The first button is connected to D1 (GPIO**5**) , the second button is connected to D2 (GPIO**5**) and the buzzer is connected to D6 (GPIO**12**).

#define the pins used by the buttons
#also initialise the buttons as INPUT, PULL_UP 
button1 = Pin(5, Pin.IN, Pin.PULL_UP) #D1
button2 = Pin(4, Pin.IN, Pin.PULL_UP) #D2
#define the pin as OUTPUT and the PWM of the buzzer 
buzzer = PWM(Pin(12, Pin.OUT) , freq = 500)
Define the frequencies of the notes for all the 7 octaves these notes have an error because we declared them as integers and not floats.

### First song - Function

When calling this function, the buzzer will play fisrt song.
In this function, fisrt, we will define the waiting times and after create the first sequence rendering each indicated note for delay1 (or delay2, or delay3) milliseconds, then turn off the buzzer for delay4 milliseconds then play the next sequence.

#when calling this function, the buzzer will
#play the ABC Alphabet song
def abc_song():
    #define the waiting times
    sleep1 = 0.7
    sleep2 = 0.01
    sleep3 = 0.3
    sleep4 = 0.1
    
    #play every note indicated for delay1 (or delay2, or delay3)
    #milliseconds, then turn off the buzzer for delay4 milliseconds
    #then play the next note
    
    #first sequence
    #play: C C G G A A G
    buzzer.freq(c7)
    sleep(sleep1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(sleep4)
    
    buzzer.freq(c7)
    sleep(sleep1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(sleep4)
    
    buzzer.duty(g7)
    sleep(sleep1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(sleep4)
    
    buzzer.duty(g7)
    sleep(sleep1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(sleep4)
    
    buzzer.duty(a7)
    sleep(sleep1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(sleep4)
    
    buzzer.duty(a7)
    sleep(sleep1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(sleep4)
    
    buzzer.duty(g7)
    sleep(sleep1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(sleep4)

### Second song - Function
When calling this function, the buzzer will play the Old Mcdonald had a farm song.

The code is the same as for the first song, the difference being the musical notes.

#when calling this function, the buzzer will
#play the Old Mcdonald had a farm song
def old_mcdonald():
    #play every note indicated for time1 (or time2, 
    #or time3, or time4, or time5) milliseconds, 
    #then turn off the buzzer for time0 milliseconds
    #then play the next note
    time0 = 0.1
    time1 = 0.3
    time2 = 0.6
    time3 = 0.9
    time4 = 0.55
    time5 = 0.2

    #first part
    #play: C C C G A A G
    buzzer.freq(c4)
    sleep(time1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(time0)
    
    buzzer.freq(c4)
    sleep(time1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(time0)
    
    buzzer.duty(c4)
    sleep(time1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(time0)
    
    buzzer.duty(g3)
    sleep(time1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(time0)
    
    buzzer.duty(a4)
    sleep(time1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(time0)
    
    buzzer.duty(a4)
    sleep(time1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(time0)
    
    buzzer.duty(g3)
    sleep(time1)
    buzzer.deinit()
    sleep(time0)

### Infinite loop

We will create an infinite loop ('while True') for the board to execute the instructions continuously.

In the this while loop we have to read the state of the button using button.value(), and if the first button is pressed (button.value() == 0), the buzzer will turn on first song, same for the second song.

#for board execute the instructions continuously we make an infinite loop
while True:
    # read the current state of the button
    #if the first button is pressed, turn on first song
    if button1.value() == 0:
        #play ABC Alphabet song
        abc_song()
    #if the second button was pressed, play the second song
    elif button2.value() == 0:
        #play the second song
        old_mcdonald()

Next step is to gently connect the development board to the computer via the
included micro USB cable. There is only one way to plug it in, do not use force to
insert the cable.

To compile the code you should follow the instructions for the board *Adafruit CLUE* from this link:
https://youtu.be/F_4GXU8kKfk?t=585

**Congratulations**, you have completed the tutorial!
